- tIntuitive vs Analytical Thinking: Four Perspectives -- tHistory and Philosophy of Mathematics -- tWhy Did Lagrange "Prove" the Parallel Postulate -- tKronecker's Algorithmic Mathematics -- tIndiscrete Variations on Gian-Carlo Rota's Themes -- tCircle Packing: A Personal Reminiscence -- tApplying Inconsistent Mathematics -- tWhy Do We Believe Theorems -- tMathematics in the Media -- tMathematicians Solve 45-Year-Old Kervaire Invariant Puzzle -- tDarwin: The Reluctant Mathematician -- tLoves Me, Loves Me Not (Do the Math) -- tThe Mysterious Equilibrium of Zombies and Other Things Mathematicians See at the Movies -- tStrength in Numbers: On Mathematics and Musical Rhythm -- tMath-hattan -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis anthology brings together the year's finest writing on mathematics from around the world. Featuring promising new voices alongside some of the foremost names in mathematics, The Best Writing on Mathematics makes available to a wide audience many articles not easily found anywhere else--and you don't need to be a mathematician to enjoy them. These writings offer surprising insights into the nature, meaning, and practice of mathematics today. They delve into the history, philosophy, teaching, and everyday occurrences of math, and take readers behind the scenes of today's hottest mathematical debates. Here readers will discover why Freeman Dyson thinks some mathematicians are birds while others are frogs; why Keith Devlin believes there's more to mathematics than proof; what Nick Paumgarten has to say about the timing patterns of New York City's traffic lights (and why jaywalking is the most mathematically efficient way to cross Sixty-sixth Street); what Samuel Arbesman can tell us about the epidemiology of the undead in zombie flicks; and much, much more. In addition to presenting the year's most memorable writing on mathematics, this must-have anthology also includes a foreword by esteemed mathematician William Thurston and an informative introduction by Mircea Pitici. This book belongs on the shelf of anyone interested in where math has taken us--and where it's headed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMathematics. 7aMATHEMATICS / General.2bisacsh1 aAcker, Kathleen Ambruso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlderson, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArbesman, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowers, Philip L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCellucci, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCipra, Barry A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColyvan, Mark Colyvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Chandler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevlin, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickenstein, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyson, Freeman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Harold M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGowers, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabiner, Judith V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Mary W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrünbaum, Branko, econtrib